Files:
- e2e/execute-script-semantics.e2e.ts (new file — contains all tests listed in acceptance criteria)

Context:
This is the regression net for issue #79. The behavior we want to pin down mirrors how Chrome DevTools console and Node REPL evaluate user input: a single expression evaluates and returns its value; multi-statement input uses function-body semantics with `return`. Without E2E coverage, someone could revert the expression-first fallback and only the wrapper-string unit test would catch it (easy to ignore). Real E2E ensures the whole pipeline — MCP tool → writeExecFile → chrome.scripting.executeScript(files, MAIN) → result polling → structuredClone serialization → MCP response — actually returns the right values.

Reference file to model the new E2E after: e2e/browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts. It already uses browser_execute_script (line 265, 419) to read `document.readyState`. Copy its imports, fixture use, and `parseToolResult` helper pattern.

Example test shape (pattern to follow for every case):
```typescript
test('bare IIFE expression returns its value (GitHub #79)', async ({ opentabsServer, testServer }) => {
  const { mcpClient } = opentabsServer;
  const openResult = await mcpClient.callTool('browser_open_tab', { url: testServer.url });
  const tabInfo = parseToolResult(openResult.content);
  const tabId = tabInfo.id as number;
  // wait for load — reuse the waitFor pattern from browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts

  const result = await mcpClient.callTool('browser_execute_script', {
    tabId,
    code: '(function(){return 42})()',
  });
  expect(result.isError).toBe(false);
  const data = parseToolResult(result.content);
  const value = (data.value as { value: unknown }).value;
  expect(value).toBe(42);
});
```

The shape `(data.value as { value: unknown }).value` matches what browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts already does (line 271-272: `const value = data.value as Record<string, unknown> | undefined; return value?.value === 'complete';`). The outer `value` is the dispatch result envelope and inner `value` is the captured user-code result.

Test server: use a simple HTTP server like the other E2E files do (e2e/analyze-site-test-server.ts is a reference for a local server). Alternatively, many E2E tests just use `testServer` from the fixture. Check e2e/fixtures.ts for the available `testServer` fixture — if it already serves a simple page, use that directly. Don't build a new server just for these tests.

Important structural points for the worker writing these tests:
- **All tests should share a single `beforeAll` or per-test tab open** to avoid spawning a new Chromium context per test case. Look at how e2e/browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts structures its tests.
- **Use the exact same wait-for-page-load pattern** as browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts lines 255-280 — this is an established pattern in the repo.
- **Every `code:` string must be a single string literal** — the same exact bytes that a user would pass via the MCP API. Do NOT pre-process, pre-wrap, or JSON.stringify the code strings in the test; the whole point is that user code goes in verbatim.
- **For the error-path tests**, assert that `result.isError` is `false` (the tool call itself succeeds — the error is carried in the envelope's `error` field), OR follow whatever convention the existing code uses for user-script errors. Inspect the shape of `data.value` when the wrapper writes `{ error: '...' }`: according to extension-commands.ts:423-444, the full `{ error }` object is returned as-is. So the assertion is `expect((data.value as { error?: string }).error).toBe('boom')`.
- **For the ReferenceError test**, the specific message text varies by V8 version — assert `expect((data.value as { error?: string }).error).toMatch(/nonexistentVariable|is not defined/i)` instead of an exact match.
- **For the `undefined` test**, use a code string like `void 0` or `(function(){})()` — an expression evaluating to undefined. The extension normalizes undefined to null at extension-commands.ts:429, so the assertion is `expect(value).toBe(null)`.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change any production source files (platform/**) in this story — US-001 owns that. This story is pure test coverage.
- Do NOT add new Playwright config or new fixtures — reuse e2e/fixtures.ts.
- Do NOT disable or skip any existing tests.
- Do NOT start a new test server of your own — use the `testServer` fixture from e2e/fixtures.ts (see how e2e/browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts uses it).
- Do NOT put the new test file in a subdirectory — flat layout at e2e/execute-script-semantics.e2e.ts matches the convention used by every other E2E file.
- Do NOT commit test-server HTML — if you need a custom page, use `testServer.setResponse(...)` or equivalent from the fixture (check fixtures.ts for what's available).
- **Trap warning**: the existing tests use `opentabsServer` or similar fixture name for the MCP client + server combo. Grep e2e/fixtures.ts to find the exact fixture name before wiring up the test file. Using the wrong fixture name will fail type-check.
- **Trap warning**: browser_execute_script returns a structured content block. The `parseToolResult` helper is defined in a shared helper file — check e2e/browser-chrome-apis.e2e.ts imports for where it comes from. Don't re-implement it.
- **Trap warning**: test timeouts — some tests (top-level await, Promise resolution) may need extra time. Use the existing EXEC_MAX_ASYNC_WAIT_MS-respecting patterns. The default test timeout should be fine (Playwright's default is 30s), but don't add artificial `waitForTimeout` calls.

Verification you can do locally after writing:
- `cd platform/mcp-server && npm run build` — wrapper rewrite compiled
- `npm run type-check` — E2E file type-checks
- `npm run test:e2e -- execute-script-semantics` — new E2E file passes
- Manual sanity: the exact reproducer from the GitHub issue — `(function(){return 42})()` — returns `{ value: 42 }` via `opentabs tool call browser_execute_script` against any loaded tab.
